### English Translation

Three hours after getting off work and heading home to surf the internet, I saw people mourning #YuYingshi. At the time, the only thing I knew about him was that he was the idol of the famous blogger #WongWaiHung. Apart from that, I knew nothing of his life.

However, in the 21st century, you don't always need to ask a "teacher." With Google, you can know everything about the world. After searching for a while, I gradually understood why he was so famous and why Professor Wong loved to mention Master Yu...

Master Yu was a professor at three Ivy League schools! How awesome is that? Just the fact alone is terrifying!

I acted like a stalker, constantly digging up Yu Yingshi's background: How does the Chinese Wikipedia describe him? How does the English Wikipedia describe him? How did people praise him when he won awards? What do today's obituaries say? A person I respect most floated into my mind... Teacher Yun Gen. They really are quite similar!

Unfortunately, Teacher Gen doesn't have a chair at Harvard University, but their traditional Chinese Kung Fu of "knowing the past and present" and "I am China" is definitely of the same origin. Teacher Gen likes Taoism and Buddhism, while Master Yu seems to be a fan of Confucianism.

But that's where the trouble lies.

Confucianism emphasizes benevolence, righteousness, propriety, wisdom, and trust; it stresses the proper order between the old and the young, and the correct relationship between ruler and subject. However, if you studied at a top American university, earned your PhD during the height of the hippie movement, and returned, do you really think you can go around teaching people to "respect teachers and value the Way" and not indulge in so much "individualism"? You'd be stuck.

So, how does a scholar avoid being stuck? This is the knowledge that Confucius spent his whole life struggling to acquire, and Confucian disciples could not possibly be unaware of it: In Confucius's time, the world was on the brink of chaos. He traveled through various states hoping to secure an official position and achieve great things. However, he only knew how to recite the rites of the Duke of Zhou and failed to cater to the needs of his bosses, so he returned empty-handed. But failure is the mother of success; his students improved greatly. As Sima Qian said: "The seventy disciples scattered among the feudal lords; the great ones became teachers, ministers, and high officials, while the lesser ones befriended and taught the scholar-officials." Why was this?

Because after a few generations of inheritance, they began to understand the subtle expressions of the monarchs. By the time of Mencius, his interactions with the rulers were different; he could joke and chat, and knew how to flatter his boss: "Your Majesty, I see you can't bear to kill even a cow; you must be a benevolent ruler! Practicing the Way of Benevolence is feasible!"

By the late Warring States period, the "Confucian" strategists had mastered the game of "monarch interviews." To get a job, they threw away "benevolence" and "propriety" entirely, and everyone went to study "rule by law," this new technology. So, Xunzi, as a Confucian disciple, produced students who could become high officials in the Qin Shi Huang government. If you look at Li Si, you can't smell even a hint of Confucius's spirit.

Today, with over two hundred nations in the United Nations, the situation is more complex than in the Spring and Autumn period. If Confucian successors leave China, this land of ancient rituals, and go to the barbaric land of military hegemony, the United States, do you really think they will pull out the *Analects* and tell people to observe "three years of mourning"? Everyone knows how miserable Confucius was when he and his students were turned away at every door. So, when they went to America, Confucius's disciples naturally said that the Master supported "democracy," "democracy is great," and "the Communist Party is doomed." Only then could they become Ivy League professors!

Someone might ask: "Doesn't saying nonsense have consequences?" Of course not! Confucius and Mencius died over two thousand years ago, and the Confucian tradition was smashed during the May Fourth Movement. As the top academic authority in the world's only superpower after World War II, you could say that Johnny Kung taught people to take drugs and play with women, and someone might still believe it. After all, American "theoretical nuclear weapons" are solid stuff; the consequences of the Japanese not believing in evil were vividly remembered back then.

So, why could Master Yu simply translate a few sentences from the *Book of Han* into English and get a PhD, and why were several universities willing to hire him as a professor? #YouKnow. Pushing you onto the pedestal to become an authority is just to make you speak with your teeth clenched: "Everyone here is a wax duck; you think Confucius's thought is feudal? Oh, what a big misunderstanding! Actually, he was a democrat! If you don't have a Harvard chair, just listen to the lecture!"

As for whether Confucian thought conflicts with democracy? Honestly, these things, "Sinologists" know nothing about. You say: The Republic of China is an example. Hey boss, is Taiwan's political system really "Confucian"? The KMT bosses constantly curse Tsai Ing-wen; is that how Confucianism plays? Did Tsai Ing-wen ever perform the ritual of bowing to heaven and earth? No. The spirit of science, not being a shaman, goes against the Confucian purpose. Do you think using Chinese characters makes you Confucian? Do you think Confucianism can only exist in China?

As I mentioned earlier, Japan is Confucian, and Britain is Confucian (at least among advanced nations, they are the most similar to Confucianism): The ruler speaks of ritual and grandeur, power is bestowed by heaven, supreme and untouchable, everyone is in a hierarchical layer, no one can challenge across ranks, and only then is society stable. As for the successes and failures of their democratic systems, that is not something an American-Chinese person is qualified to comment on.

---

### Commentary and Main Point

**Disregarding the sarcastic tone, what is the main point the author is trying to convey?**

The author's central argument is a critique of the intellectual compromise and historical revisionism exhibited by certain Sinologists (specifically Yu Yingshi) who achieved prominence in Western academia. The author contends that:

1.  **Incompatibility of Core Values:** The author argues that traditional Confucianism, with its emphasis on hierarchy, loyalty to authority, and ritual order, is fundamentally incompatible with the liberal democratic values and individualism prevalent in modern Western academia.
2.  **Strategic Adaptation for Career Success:** The author suggests that Yu Yingshi and his peers did not genuinely reconcile Confucianism with democracy. Instead, they strategically reinterpreted Confucian texts to align with Western expectations (portraying Confucius as a proto-democrat) solely to secure prestigious positions (like Ivy League professorships) and academic authority in the United States.
3.  **The "Wax Duck" Metaphor:** The author uses the metaphor of the "wax duck" (a figure that looks real but is hollow) to describe how these scholars are elevated to authority figures. They are expected to perform a specific narrative that validates Western academic dominance, even if it distorts historical reality.
4.  **Critique of "Sinology" as a Western Construct:** The essay implies that the Western academic definition of "Confucianism" is often a projection of Western values rather than an accurate reflection of the tradition. The author points out that actual Confucian societies (like historical China or even modern Japan/UK in terms of social structure) prioritize hierarchy and stability over the kind of democratic individualism that Western Sinologists claim to find in Confucian texts.

In essence, the author views Yu Yingshi's work not as a sincere scholarly bridge between East and West, but as a calculated performance of intellectual conformity to gain status in a Western-dominated academic system, effectively silencing the true, hierarchical nature of Confucian thought. [end of text]


